properties.description: Named for Phil and John Acuff, residential developers in Lenexa and Shawnee.
William Alden owned 10 acres from one mile west of Shawnee and donated land for the Greenwood School.
Robert O. and Frances Allman were landowners of an area north of 79th and west of Lackman Road.
Originally called Chase Road after the Chase family; later renamed Antioch because the Antioch Church was located there.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division

properties.description: Named for John N. Ballentine, grocer from Kansas City, Kansas who moved to Johnson County in 1919.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division

properties.description: John L. Barkley helped develop the area and was on the Mission Urban Township board.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division

properties.description: John Barton was the treasurer of Johnson County in 1857 and founder of Olathe.
Blackbob was the recognized chief of the Black Bob Band of Shawnee Indians in the Stanley  Stillwell area.
Could have been named for the famed Bluejacket spring used by Indians for water. - OR - The Shawnee Indians of White decent, Charles, Julia and Robert Bluejacket.
New street west of Loiret Boulevard in the Villas of Loriet.
Named for the family of Squire Charles A. Bradshaw, one of the founders of Lenexa.
Well-known member of Overland Park and Olathe areas; a portion of this street was renamed Switzer.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division

properties.description: Named for Remi Caenen, Belgium immigrant who moved to the area in the 1860s.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division

properties.description: Named after Cedar Creek, small stream that enters Kansas about 1  miles east of De Soto.
Believed to have been named after the Cherry Lane School located at 95th and Woodland.
Some people believe it was named after Buffalo Bill Cody.
Name changed from 111th street after the construction of the Johnson County Community College.

Named after the Conser family. John Conser was a pioneer farmer and prize winning honey raiser at 80th and Metcalf. Grant Conser (Johns son) bought several lots at the first auction of lots in the new Overland Park plats, built several businesses on the lots and a fine new home on 80th Street.
properties.source: Overland Park Community Development Dept. Comprehensive Planning Division
